Author::::feliciafarrel
DateTime::::2016-03-11T13:28:00Z
My own family's experience goes some way to explain this. My great great grandfather was your farmer, except in a different business. During the war he took advantage of the Government's need to build a sizeable business empire. Sure enough he passed it down to children. That generation, my grandfather's, carried on reasonably altruistically expanding the business a little, diversifying and employing more people. Things started to go wrong in my father's generation. By this time the shareholding was split among four sons. One was a lazy greedy idiot. One was a determinedly independent professional. The other two we semi-competent businessmen with large families. The empire was basically divided into four and frittered away with more or less morality, depending on the morals of each son. I was a lucky child, I got a very good education at a well known girls public school, thanks to my great great grandfather's efforts mainly, and the fact that my Dad was a decent guy.



Author::::feliciafarrel
DateTime::::2016-03-11T13:27:20Z
2. So without the profit motive will farmers or employers even exist? I draw on my own first hand experience here of starting three small businesses, the first two of which failed and left me bankrupt and temporarily homeless. It's arguable that my hubby and I may have started the first one, being young energetic and naive without the prospect of rich rewards, but no way would we have tried again after the heartache and stress of the first failure.  I always smile when I see people (the vast majority) glibly referring to people starting their own business (the way you talk about the farmer for instance in your example). Unless you have tried yourself to borrow money, take on employees, persuade people to buy your product, deal with all the admin, the tax, the supply chain, and all the other myriad responsibilities – you are in no position to comment really. In my life I have been a business owner and employee, and there is a reason why most people end up as employees, and it has little to do with lack of money or luck, and a lot to do with the huge stresses that owning your own business places on you – just worrying about my staff and my next tax bill used to keep me awake night after night. And the hours that an average start up business owner has to work make junior doctors look like they are on permanent holiday.



