Author::::ID9665292
DateTime::::2016-03-10T13:41:43Z
My husband, from a poor Irish working-class family, put himself through University (no grants) by working and with the assistance of his parents, who prioritised saving for their family needs. We did not expect to own a house, but managed to do so when we were in our 30s, which was also when we could afford to have children. Throughout our lives we have saved to be able to assist our children and grandchildren with housing/education etc. Money has always circulated freely within the family — distributed according to need, regardless of generational considerations. Both myself and my daughter were able to stay at home to look after our children because the men in the family did not consider themselves as 'individuals' but as part of a family unit whose concerted efforts benefited all. The State has inserted itself in our lives more and more since the 70s and has made it much more difficult to run our lives in this way, but I still believe this 'family' modus vivendi is a tried and tested way to achieve contentment and meaning in life. We try to depend on the State for as little as possible. We may need its assistance in periods of great hardship but, in the last analysis, it can never be anything but a 'mechanism' of survival.



